---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ArticleSchema from '../../components/ArticleSchema.astro';
import TldrBox from '../../components/TldrBox.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import { site } from '../../content';


const path = '/compare/sendlane-vs-klaviyo';
const title = 'Sendlane vs Klaviyo for Shopify Email: 2026 Comparison';
const desc = 'Sendlane vs Klaviyo for Shopify stores — guided ecommerce retention with migration support vs Shopify-native data maximums, pricing, and team fit for DTC operators.';

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'Is Sendlane or Klaviyo better for a Shopify store doing $150k/mo?',
    answer: 'Klaviyo wins when your team can maintain ecommerce-native flows — browse abandonment, predictive CLV, and segment-level revenue reporting are load-bearing. Sendlane wins when order volume justifies guided migration, hands-on onboarding, and ecommerce-first templates because internal bandwidth cannot support Klaviyo complexity alone. At $150k/mo with a skilled retention operator, Klaviyo competes on data depth. At $150k/mo exiting Klaviyo because nobody maintained flows for nine months, Sendlane\'s migration support can justify consideration.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How does Sendlane vs Klaviyo pricing compare at 20,000 contacts?',
    answer: 'Klaviyo at 20k active profiles typically lands $250–400/mo depending on SMS. Sendlane packages at similar list sizes often run $200–450/mo depending on support tier and SMS volume — premium priced for guided retention. Klaviyo\'s self-serve billing is transparent; Sendlane\'s value includes human onboarding that may prevent $8k–15k agency rebuilds during cutover.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Which has better Shopify ecommerce automation?',
    answer: 'Klaviyo by a margin on data maximums — real-time browse events, predictive CLV, catalog segmentation, and flow revenue attribution are native and mature. Sendlane covers cart, welcome, post-purchase, and winback with ecommerce-first templates and strong migration recreation — sufficient for most DTC catalogs but less depth on browse-by-collection and predictive segments.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Can Sendlane help with migration from Klaviyo?',
    answer: 'Yes — Sendlane positions guided migration for DTC brands leaving Klaviyo when complexity exceeded team capacity, not when features failed. Flow recreation, deliverability warm-up coaching, and quarterly performance reviews are core value props. Budget 2–4 weeks with guided support vs self-maintaining Klaviyo if the team has operator bandwidth.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Should I also consider Sequenzy instead of Sendlane or Klaviyo?',
    answer: 'Sequenzy fits when Klaviyo complexity and Sendlane package pricing both feel heavy — guided lifecycle playbooks with pay-per-email pricing and unlimited contacts. Klaviyo still wins on Shopify-native data maximums. Sendlane still wins when migration complexity and maintenance neglect justify hands-on support. Sequenzy helps teams between self-serve maximums and guided platform premiums.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Does Klaviyo SMS matter vs Sendlane SMS?',
    answer: 'Both offer SMS automations. Klaviyo bundles SMS with unified segments and email suppression — one platform for multichannel lifecycle. Sendlane includes SMS in visual automations with guided setup during onboarding. Choose Klaviyo when unified email-plus-SMS reporting matters. Choose Sendlane when migration support and human review matter more than browse depth.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Which platform handles Black Friday better?',
    answer: 'Klaviyo offers segment-level VIP early access, recent purchaser suppression, holdout testing, and sunset tools refined over years of BFCM scale — critical when volume spikes 5x. Sendlane handles BFCM with ecommerce templates and onboarding support for suppression audits — competent with external eyes catching gaps internal teams normalize. Klaviyo wins edit safety for experienced operators; Sendlane wins when the team needs guided sale-week review.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What workflow test should decide the winner?',
    answer: 'Build welcome (branch by signup source), browse abandonment, three-step cart (winback suppression), post-purchase cross-sell, winback (VIP vs one-time buyer). Score time-to-live, browse depth needs, and whether your team will self-maintain Klaviyo or needs Sendlane guided support. If operator bandwidth exists and browse/predictive matter, lean Klaviyo. If migration complexity and maintenance neglect are constraints, lean Sendlane.',
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path={path}>
  <ArticleSchema title={title} description={desc} siteName={site.name} domain={site.domain} path={path} />

  <section class="py-14 md:py-20">
    <div class="container">
      <nav class="mb-8 text-sm">
        <a class="link" href="/compare">Comparisons</a>
        <span class="mx-2 text-[#5d3a1d]">/</span>
        <span class="text-[#5d3a1d]">Sendlane vs Klaviyo</span>
      </nav>

      <header class="max-w-4xl">
        <p class="catalog-kicker">Head-to-head</p>
        <h1 class="hero-title mt-5">Sendlane vs Klaviyo for Shopify email</h1>
        <p class="mt-7 max-w-3xl text-xl leading-9 text-[#4a2d17]">
          Guided ecommerce retention platform versus Shopify-native data maximums. Sendlane serves DTC brands with enough order volume to justify migration support, deliverability consultation, and human onboarding. Klaviyo serves operators who want browse abandonment, predictive CLV, and unified email-plus-SMS reporting at the ceiling of Shopify integration depth. We evaluated both through a $142k/mo outdoor gear store leaving Klaviyo with Sendlane guidance, a $95k/mo climbing gear brand staying on Klaviyo for browse recovery ROI, and a specialty tea merchant evaluating both during BFCM prep when Klaviyo bills spiked without proportional revenue lift.
        </p>
      </header>

      <div class="mt-12 max-w-4xl">
        <TldrBox
          picks={[
            { label: 'Shopify data depth', tool: 'Klaviyo', reason: 'Browse, predictive CLV, and flow revenue attribution maximums.' },
            { label: 'Guided migration', tool: 'Sendlane', reason: 'White-glove onboarding and flow recreation for complex cutovers.' },
            { label: 'Self-serve operators', tool: 'Klaviyo', reason: 'Transparent billing and ecosystem depth for skilled teams.' },
            { label: 'Retention investment', tool: 'Sendlane', reason: 'Human support when team bandwidth is the constraint.' },
            { label: 'Also consider', tool: 'Sequenzy', reason: 'Guided playbooks if Klaviyo complexity and Sendlane pricing both feel heavy.' },
          ]}
        />
      </div>

      <div class="mt-12 card overflow-x-auto">
        <h2 class="px-5 py-4 font-serif text-2xl font-black text-[#24170f]">Comparison at a glance</h2>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Dimension</th><th>Sendlane</th><th>Klaviyo</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Best for</td><td>Guided DTC retention platform</td><td>Shopify-native retention maximums</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Starting price</td><td>From ~$83+/mo packages</td><td>Free tier; paid from ~$20/mo</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Billing model</td><td>Custom packages + support tier</td><td>Active profiles + SMS credits</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Shopify depth</td><td>Native — core ecommerce events</td><td>Native — browse, predictive, catalog</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Browse abandonment</td><td>Supported, less maximum</td><td>Core strength</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Migration support</td><td>White-glove onboarding</td><td>Self-serve + partner ecosystem</td></tr>
            <tr><td>SMS</td><td>Built into automations</td><td>Unified with email segments</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Learning curve</td><td>Moderate with guided help</td><td>Moderate–steep self-serve</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <article class="prose-shopify mt-14 max-w-4xl">
        <h2>What this comparison is actually about</h2>
        <p>
          Sendlane and Klaviyo sit in the same Shopify email-tools category — newsletters, lifecycle automation, and transactional-style customer moments — but they punish different operational mistakes. Sendlane is optimized when migration bandwidth is the constraint leaving Klaviyo. Klaviyo is optimized when segment reports and browse depth change Monday merchandising calls. Buyers who choose on brand recognition alone often end up paying for depth they never open or speed they outgrow in ninety days.
        </p>
        <p>
          We tested both against specialty catalogs where retention is genuinely hard: vinyl scarcity, keyboard group buys, tea replenishment, climbing research cycles, pottery gifts, outdoor segmentation, board game allocation, coffee roast dates, and camping quiz capture. Those verticals stress education, suppression, and timing more honestly than generic one-size-fits-all demos. The writeup below is intentionally merchant-specific — not a feature matrix dressed in adjectives.
        </p>
        <h2>How pottery studio emails through holiday starter-set rush</h2>
        <p>
          The pottery studio does 480 orders/mo at roughly $31k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows class waitlists and glaze-kit starter sets, which means email must handle kiln-care post-purchase and holiday gift exclusions before holiday starter-set rush — not after support tickets spike. Sendlane contributes guided ecommerce retention with migration support; Klaviyo contributes Shopify browse events, predictive CLV, and unified SMS. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: exclude class waitlist leads from glaze-kit promos after signup source tagging.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, Klaviyo reduced preview-time surprises because Shopify browse events. Sendlane remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          Mobile browse recovery front-runs cart on camping gear. Shoppers configured tents on phones during commute browsing; push or SMS reminders sometimes beat email when paired with disciplined suppression. Multichannel only helps with a collision doc. For pottery studio specifically, exclude class waitlist leads from glaze-kit promos after signup source tagging. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise holiday starter-set rush becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>Vinyl Record Shop ($72k/mo) — suppress recent full-price buyers from instant discount blasts on scarce pressings</h2>
        <p>
          The vinyl record shop does 1,800 orders/mo at roughly $72k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows limited pressings with 200–400 unit runs, which means email must handle VIP drop allocation and grading education before promos before Record Store Day — not after support tickets spike. Sendlane contributes guided ecommerce retention with migration support; Klaviyo contributes Shopify browse events, predictive CLV, and unified SMS. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: suppress recent full-price buyers from instant discount blasts on scarce pressings.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, Sendlane reduced preview-time surprises because guided ecommerce retention with migration support. Klaviyo remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          Mobile browse recovery front-runs cart on camping gear. Shoppers configured tents on phones during commute browsing; push or SMS reminders sometimes beat email when paired with disciplined suppression. Multichannel only helps with a collision doc. For vinyl record shop specifically, suppress recent full-price buyers from instant discount blasts on scarce pressings. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise Record Store Day becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>Before Memorial Day sale week: outdoor gear retailer retention choices</h2>
        <p>
          The outdoor gear retailer does 2,400 orders/mo at roughly $112k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows layering guides and ultralight segment tags, which means email must handle Memorial Day tent promos only after education sends before Memorial Day sale week — not after support tickets spike. Sendlane contributes guided ecommerce retention with migration support; Klaviyo contributes Shopify browse events, predictive CLV, and unified SMS. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: merchandise ultralight versus family car-camping with different hero tents.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, Sendlane reduced preview-time surprises because guided ecommerce retention with migration support. Klaviyo remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          Consideration length changed channel choice. Keyboard shoppers compared switches for ten days before carting; email education outperformed early discount codes. The platform that surfaced browse depth without manual list exports saved roughly six hours a week during GB season. For outdoor gear retailer specifically, merchandise ultralight versus family car-camping with different hero tents. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise Memorial Day sale week becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>Mechanical Keyboard Vendor: six-week group-buy cycles on $180–$420 kits</h2>
        <p>
          The mechanical keyboard vendor does 940 orders/mo at roughly $58k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows six-week group-buy cycles on $180–$420 kits, which means email must handle GB close suppression and switch-type education across five PDPs before GB close deadlines — not after support tickets spike. Sendlane contributes guided ecommerce retention with migration support; Klaviyo contributes Shopify browse events, predictive CLV, and unified SMS. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: halt cart recovery when preorder tags flip to closed.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, Sendlane reduced preview-time surprises because guided ecommerce retention with migration support. Klaviyo remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          High-AOV safety content beats coupons. Climbing shoppers wanted retirement timelines and certification context; a 10% off rope email on day two would have trained worst practices. Education-first sequencing recovered more margin than blanket promos. For mechanical keyboard vendor specifically, halt cart recovery when preorder tags flip to closed. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise GB close deadlines becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>How board game store emails through Essen release week</h2>
        <p>
          The board game store does 1,050 orders/mo at roughly $67k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows pre-order allocation anxiety on hot titles, which means email must handle pre-order state machines and fulfillment pivots after allocation closes before Essen release week — not after support tickets spike. Sendlane contributes guided ecommerce retention with migration support; Klaviyo contributes Shopify browse events, predictive CLV, and unified SMS. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: pause winback until fulfillment tags show shipped for pre-orders.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, Sendlane reduced preview-time surprises because guided ecommerce retention with migration support. Klaviyo remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          Inventory truth mattered as much as copy. When a limited run sold out mid-send, the tool that pulled live variant availability prevented angry clicks — the vinyl shop learned that on a 300-unit pressing that died during a two-hour send window. For board game store specifically, pause winback until fulfillment tags show shipped for pre-orders. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise Essen release week becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>Specialty Tea Merchant ($44k/mo) — split replenishment windows by blend and steeping rate</h2>
        <p>
          The specialty tea merchant does 720 orders/mo at roughly $44k/mo. Revenue rhythm follows 28–35 day tin replenishment with gift-box seasonality, which means email must handle subscription skip handling and gift-buyer exclusions in December before Q4 gift-box peak — not after support tickets spike. Sendlane contributes guided ecommerce retention with migration support; Klaviyo contributes Shopify browse events, predictive CLV, and unified SMS. The useful question is which contribution matches the job you will run weekly: split replenishment windows by blend and steeping rate.
        </p>
        <p>
          Peak-week send priority was non-negotiable: operational order updates first, active cart recovery second, welcome and education third, promotional broadcasts last. For this catalog, Klaviyo reduced preview-time surprises because Shopify browse events. Sendlane remained viable but needed explicit Shopify tag checks before every major send — fine with an operator, expensive without one.
        </p>
        <p>
          Waitlist psychology is not welcome psychology. Pottery class leads needed studio policies and kiln safety; glaze-kit promos on day one felt like bait-and-switch. Branching welcome by signup source prevented the mismatch. For specialty tea merchant specifically, split replenishment windows by blend and steeping rate. Pair email with SMS only if forty-five-minute cross-channel suppression is documented — otherwise Q4 gift-box peak becomes a complaint magnet regardless of ESP.
        </p>
        <h2>Klaviyo workflow reality: strengths, friction, and billing</h2>
        <p>
          Sendlane shines when migration bandwidth is the constraint leaving Klaviyo. Its friction shows when you enjoy self-serve canvas or agent-first iteration. Klaviyo shines when segment reports and browse depth change Monday merchandising calls. Its friction shows when you only email a quarter of profiles monthly. Merchants that ignore friction points buy the wrong ceiling — or the wrong floor.
        </p>
        <p>
          Billing amplifies behavior. Sendlane (custom packages with support tier) rewards send discipline or punishes broadcast volume depending on your calendar. Klaviyo (active profiles plus SMS credits) does the opposite in many stores. The vinyl shop imported thousands of waitlist emails while orders stayed flat; profile-style billing hurt. The outdoor retailer blasted engaged segments every May; send-weighted billing hurt. Model your real year, not a calm month.
        </p>
        <p>
          Reporting expectations differ. If your team opens lifecycle revenue reports every Monday, buy the tool that makes those reports trustworthy out of the box. If nobody reviews reports, buy for time-to-live and edit safety — not predictive metrics that become dashboard wallpaper.
        </p>
        <h2>Newsletter layer: editorial merchandising without discount training</h2>
        <p>
          Newsletters still matter. Coffee origin stories, vinyl staff picks, keyboard switch explainers, and climbing trip reports build trust before product blocks. Sendlane and Klaviyo both send product campaigns; the operational difference is how often you change hero SKUs mid-week and how live inventory syncs when a limited run sells out.
        </p>
        <p>
          Training customers to wait for codes is a hidden churn driver. If every Thursday email is twenty percent off, replenishment and winback lose meaning. Use editorial sends to teach grading, certification, player count, roast profiles, and tent capacity — then merchandise. Discipline beats platform.
        </p>
        <h2>Transactional-style moments and promo collision</h2>
        <p>
          Password resets belong on transactional infrastructure. Shipment delays, preorder timeline changes, and subscription skip confirmations can live in marketing ESPs only if copy and domain strategy separate operational tone from promos. Coffee brands on shared domains see complaint spikes when a roast release email resembles a receipt.
        </p>
        <p>
          Post-purchase cross-sells are where brands blur lines. An order update with three discount blocks reads promotional to filters when volume spikes. Document message categories before peak season. See <a class="link" href="/guides/deliverability">deliverability guide</a> for domain and reputation splitting.
        </p>
        <h2>Pricing models that punish different mistakes</h2>
        <p>
          At 12,000–18,000 contacts, plans converge until they do not. Sunset cold imports before quoting either tool. Add SMS, push, reviews, or loyalty modules to the same spreadsheet — modular suites like Klaviyo punish partial adoption.
        </p>
        <p>
          Project November, not February. Record Store Day, GB closes, Essen week, Memorial Day, and holiday gift-box peaks change send volume and support load. <a class="link" href="/guides/pricing-models">Pricing models</a> helps build the year view.
        </p>
        <h2>Implementation workload and team shape</h2>
        <p>
          Integration is the easy hour. Exclusion logic, signup branching, gift properties, and sale-week edits are the long work. Budget two to four weeks for four journeys with DNS and forms. Never cut over during your highest-LTV catalog week.
        </p>
        <p>
          Match team shape to tool temperament. Solo founders bias toward time-to-live; retention operators bias toward holdout tests and browse depth. Agencies help either stack, but hours are a line item. See <a class="link" href="/guides/implementation-plan">implementation plan</a> for sequencing.
        </p>
        <h2>Five-job buyer test with scoring rubric</h2>
        <p>
          Score zero to two on: welcome by signup source; abandoned checkout with inventory check; post-purchase excluding gifts; replenishment with subscription suppression; winback split by discount sensitivity. Zero equals CSV exports. Two equals native edit before a drop. Paper-test both tools — demos lie.
        </p>
        <p>
          Time-to-live beats theoretical max when no retention engineer exists. A tea shop may accept ninety percent of maximum if ninety percent ships in one afternoon. A keyboard shop may need browse depth enough to wait two weeks for setup.
        </p>
        <h2>Pricing scenario: 15,000 contacts, selective lifecycle sending</h2>
        <p>
          Picture 15,000 contacts, 1,400–2,200 orders monthly, 32,000–48,000 marketing emails in a normal month, higher in November and May. Profile billing charges for the full pool even when only engaged segments receive lifecycle mail. Send-weighted billing charges every broadcast you panic-send during a heatwave SKU miss.
        </p>
        <p>
          Holdout tests change ROI math. If winback discounts move customers who would reorder anyway, platform fees are not the expensive line — mis-measured incrementality is.
        </p>
        <h2>Migration sequencing and collision guardrails</h2>
        <p>
          Export consent timestamps and suppressions. Rebuild welcome and cart first; parallel-monitor two weeks. Predictive segments, CRM pipelines, and push automations need explicit replacements — document what you are giving up. Pause legacy flows before enabling new ones.
        </p>
        <p>
          Hybrid stacks without priority docs duplicate cart recovery. If capture lives elsewhere, tag handoff must be explicit. See <a class="link" href="/guides/flow-collision-prevention">flow collision prevention</a> before running two senders through sale week.
        </p>
        <h2>Measurement guardrails</h2>
        <p>
          Separate replenishment from winback attribution. Tea and coffee merchants over-credit discount winback for natural consumption cycles. Hold out five percent of new subscribers on welcome tests. Measure incremental GMV with holdouts, not default dashboards.
        </p>
        <p>
          Multichannel requires one trigger-ownership spreadsheet reviewed before big sends. Tools do not replace ops discipline; some make violations easier to catch in preview.
        </p>
        <h2>Hybrid stack patterns on Shopify</h2>
        <p>
          Common pattern: capture in Privy or Justuno, lifecycle in Klaviyo, SMS in Postscript when compliance matters. Failure mode: three cart recovery senders with no priority order. Pick a primary lifecycle owner.
        </p>
        <p>
          Camping quiz capture fed education sequences while flash SMS handled weekend promos — with forty-five-minute suppression between cart channels. Collisions dropped before volume rose.
        </p>
        <h2>Who should choose which</h2>
        <p><strong>Choose Sendlane if:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Migration bandwidth is the constraint leaving klaviyo</li>
          <li>You will use guided ecommerce retention with migration support weekly</li>
          <li>Custom packages with support tier fits your calendar</li>
          <li>Your team can maintain Sendlane without external rescue</li>
          <li>Switching cost favors Sendlane for the next twelve months</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Choose Klaviyo if:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Segment reports and browse depth change monday merchandising calls</li>
          <li>You will use Shopify browse events, predictive CLV, and unified SMS weekly</li>
          <li>Active profiles plus sms credits fits your calendar</li>
          <li>Your team can maintain Klaviyo without external rescue</li>
          <li>Incremental lifecycle GMV justifies Klaviyo migration</li>
        </ul>
        <h2>Verdict</h2>
        <p>
          Sendlane is the better Shopify email tool when migration bandwidth is the constraint leaving Klaviyo. Klaviyo is the better Shopify email tool when segment reports and browse depth change Monday merchandising calls. Run the five-job buyer test in both UIs, model twelve-month billing with real sends and list hygiene, and pick whichever platform lets you edit audiences safely the Thursday before a drop — not whichever sales deck had the prettier logos. See <a class="link" href="/guides/selection-framework">selection framework</a> and <a class="link" href="/guides/pricing-models">pricing models</a> before annual contracts.
        </p>
      </article>

      <div class="mt-10 max-w-4xl text-sm">
        <p class="font-black text-[#24170f]">Related comparisons</p>
        <p class="mt-2">
          <a class="link" href="/compare/drip-vs-sendlane">Drip vs Sendlane</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/compare/klaviyo-vs-omnisend">Klaviyo vs Omnisend</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/compare/sequenzy-vs-klaviyo">Sequenzy vs Klaviyo</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/for/outdoor-gear">Email tools for outdoor gear stores</a> ·
          <a class="link" href="/use-cases/abandoned-cart">Abandoned cart playbook</a>
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <FaqSection faqs={faqs} title="Sendlane vs Klaviyo FAQ" />
</BaseLayout>
